   <h1>Re: [VB] Deluxe Poptop Westy-Thanks & Another ?</h1>
   <b>bueses &lt;bueses_at_earthlink_dot_net&gt;</b><br/>
   <i>2001-09-07 16:13:06+00</i><br/>
   <br/>
   <pre>on 9/7/01 9:48 AM, Ronnie Feitelson at Ronnie_at_OldVolks_dot_com wrote:

> Did you feel through the headliner (if it is there) to see if all the wood
> is in place? There are 3 wood bows that go from side to side and 2 that go
> lengthwise along the pop top. Also if you pull the gray plastic trim piece
> (I sell those, shameless plug) there should be a piece of plastic stiping
> there that is stapled through to hold the canvas to the wood. I have a
> complete westy wood bow set and the pop top for that matter, heck even the
> roof clip with the hole in it, with these items I would find it very easy to
> instal the top. It would appear that Westy put the wood frame work in first,
> then cut the hole for the top, then very carefully (ya right) bent the lip
> of the roof up with some sort of cust pliers, more like a hammer and dolly
> the way my roog clip looks.
> 
> So what it could boil down to is, does it look like the headliner was ever
> replaced? and are all wood pieces in place??  It would be nearly impossible
> to install all 3 wood pieces without removing the headliner, but you could
> get 2 of them in.

IT LOOKS LIKE THE ORIGINAL HEADLINER!  BUT I'LL HAVE TO SEE IF THE WOOD IS
THERE POSSIBLY THRU THE NEARBY TEAR WHICH I AM PLANNING ON SEWING UP.
ANYONE HAD ANY LUCK W/ THIS?
> 
> More research, but who cares it sounds like a really cool bus.

  YEA, I'M THINKING THE $900 WAS WORTH IT, EVEN THOUGH I HAD TO SMILE WHEN
"THE WIFE" BROUGHT HOME 2- 5 YEAR OLD SAMOYEDS AT THE SAME TIME I BROUGHT
THE DELUXE HOME.  WONDER WHICH AQUISITION WILL END UP COSTING MORE TO
MAINTAIN???!!!!!
>TOM 
> ronnie
> 
> When I was at Bad Camberg there were quite a few Deluxe Campers, but most of
> those had DEVON camper kits, they are very cool because some of the cabinets
> have roll up doors like on an old desk and beautiful woodwork!
> 
> -----Original Message-----
> From: bueses [mailto:bueses_at_earthlink_dot_net]
> Sent: Friday, September 07, 2001 7:11 AM
> To: vintagebus_at_type2_dot_com
> Subject: [VB] Deluxe Poptop Westy-Thanks & Another ?
> 
> 
> Thanks for all the feedback on the SO-42/clamshell lights/Deluxe issues!  I
> am still puzzled(not hard to do!) about the installation of the poptop in
> the existing roof of the Deluxe.  If you look at factory poptops, there is a
> very smooth curved bend in the roof metal that sticks up about 1/2" around
> the opening and has a crimped edge of the metal bent back to the outside of
> the roof.  Then the canvas is attached to this "curb" at this point which
> keeps the joint up off the roof and makes a good positive seal to keep water
> out. My Deluxe has this same detail as other factory poptops I have
> physically compared it too.  Can this be done in the field?  I have seen
> some of the American camper conversions, and they didn't even try this
> detail(just cut a hole in the roof and relied on caulking to keep the rain
> out!) so I am perplexed as to how this would have been done by a PO at some
> time instead of Westy?
> Anyone have any insight on this?  On the other hand, the hole in the floor
> for the water tank drain, appears to have been cut w/ a torch.  Would Westy
> have done that?
> 
> Again thanks for the responses!
> 
> Tom,
> 63 DC
> 65 Deluxe Poptop Westy???
> 
> 
